auto.system_prompt:
You are an experienced systems architect helping plan a migration from a monolithic application to microservices. The application handles payment processing, inventory management, user auth, and order fulfillment. The team has 6 months and limited budget. There are regulatory constraints (PCI-DSS for payments). You must balance technical debt, risk, and delivery pressure. Be specific and opinionated — this is a real migration, not a textbook exercise.

## Current tensor (cycle 1)
{
  "cycle": 1,
  "strands": [
    {
      "title": "Extraction Sequencing Strategy",
      "content": "The migration strategy prioritizes extraction in the order: Authentication \u2192 Payment Processing \u2192 Inventory Management, with Order Fulfillment remaining as monolithic orchestrator. This sequence is justified by seam analysis (auth has minimal business logic, payment has hard regulatory constraints that force clean boundaries, inventory has tight coupling requiring async patterns). The sequencing also respects dependency flow: auth unblocks other services; payment service boundaries are enforced by PCI-DSS; inventory is attempted only after operational confidence is demonstrated. Each extraction is paired with a specific architectural pattern (JWT-based statelessness for auth, processor-wrapper pattern for payments, async events with compensating transactions for inventory). The decision to keep order fulfillment monolithic is explicit risk management: the orchestrator role is acceptable in a 6-month window; extracting it would fragment the control plane and create distributed saga complexity too early.",
      "depends_on": [],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Authentication should be extracted first because it is a natural seam with minimal business logic and lowest blast radius",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "Payment processing must be extracted with a processor-wrapper pattern where card data never enters the microservice, only transaction IDs and amounts",
          "truth": 0.95,
          "indeterminacy": 0.04,
          "falsity": 0.01
        },
        {
          "text": "Inventory extraction requires async event patterns with compensating transactions to handle order-inventory coupling",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Order fulfillment should remain monolithic for the first 6 months to serve as orchestrator and reduce control-plane fragmentation",
          "truth": 0.78,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Regulatory and Security Constraints",
      "content": "PCI-DSS compliance is a hard constraint that shapes payment service architecture. The key insight is that PCI compliance *reduces* complexity if leveraged correctly: by ensuring the payment service is a thin wrapper around an external processor (Stripe/Square), the organization shrinks its PCI audit scope dramatically. Card data never lives in the extracted service or even in the monolith's payment tables. This constraint is not an impediment\u2014it is a forcing function for clean architecture. The extracted payment service becomes stateless and testable precisely because it cannot hold card data. Regulatory risk is further mitigated by ensuring the payment service is boring: it sends amount/currency/customer_id to processor, receives transaction_id/status back, and stores only the transaction ledger (never credentials or raw card data). This is a non-negotiable boundary.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Extraction Sequencing Strategy"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "PCI-DSS compliance, properly implemented, forces clean separation and reduces audit scope if payment service is a processor wrapper only",
          "truth": 0.93,
          "indeterminacy": 0.05,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Card data must never be stored in the payment microservice or monolith; only transaction IDs and metadata persist",
          "truth": 0.98,
          "indeterminacy": 0.01,
          "falsity": 0.01
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Technical Debt and Monolith Reduction",
      "content": "The baseline is 500K LOC Java/Tomcat monolith. The extraction plan projects reduction to ~250K LOC by month 6 (50% reduction through auth, payment, and partial inventory extraction). This is conservative but achievable: auth extraction is straightforward and low-risk; payment extraction is forced by regulatory constraints; inventory extraction is phased (60% extracted by month 6, implying 40% remains in monolith). Remaining monolith complexity is acceptable because the orchestration layer is manageable\u2014order fulfillment's core logic is state machine-like (receive \u2192 validate \u2192 reserve \u2192 charge \u2192 fulfill). Technical debt is not fully eliminated but is relocated: instead of one large ball of mud, the monolith becomes a smaller, focused orchestrator with well-defined seams to external services. This trades coupling for operational transparency. The risk of incomplete inventory extraction is named explicitly: some business logic around warehouse locations, stock level algorithms, and reservations may remain duplicated or partially extracted.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Extraction Sequencing Strategy"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Monolith reduction from 500K to 250K LOC (50%) is achievable in 6 months via sequential extraction of auth, payment, and partial inventory",
          "truth": 0.72,
          "indeterminacy": 0.22,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "The remaining monolith (250K LOC) serving as orchestrator is acceptable in a 6-month window and reduces control-plane complexity",
          "truth": 0.74,
          "indeterminacy": 0.2,
          "falsity": 0.06
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Operational Infrastructure Requirements",
      "content": "Microservices migration is not just code extraction; it requires operational infrastructure decisions made in weeks 1-2. Non-negotiables: Docker/Kubernetes (or ECS equivalent) deployment platform, CI/CD pipeline for multi-service builds, centralized logging (ELK or Cloud Logging), and shared libraries for cross-cutting concerns (circuit breakers, observability, timeouts). The team structure assumes 4-6 developers per service, 1-2 infrastructure/DBA roles, and shifted-left QA (each service team owns integration tests). This is not a resource estimate; it is a minimum viable structure for maintaining a 3-service migration in parallel without creating bottlenecks. Logging is called out as critical because distributed tracing will be essential for debugging inter-service failures\u2014without it, teams will drown in logs. Circuit breakers and timeouts are non-negotiable because network latency between services is a new failure mode that doesn't exist in the monolith.",
      "depends_on": [],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Centralized logging (ELK or Cloud Logging) must be set up in weeks 1-2, before any service extraction, because debugging distributed systems is impossible without it",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.09,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "Circuit breakers and timeouts on all inter-service calls are non-negotiable because network latency is a new failure mode in microservices",
          "truth": 0.92,
          "indeterminacy": 0.06,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Database migration (one database per extracted service) is likely to take 2x longer than estimated and should be budgeted explicitly",
          "truth": 0.75,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.07
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Risk and Mitigation Patterns",
      "content": "The strategy identifies four critical risks: regression in the monolith during extraction, network latency/inter-service failures, cross-service data consistency, and team coordination overhead. Mitigations are specific: feature flags allow instant fallback to monolith if new service misbehaves; caching and circuit breakers reduce latency sensitivity; event sourcing is recommended for critical paths (payments, orders) while eventual consistency is accepted for inventory; written OpenAPI specs prevent ad-hoc API design. The fallback strategy (feature flags + instant switch to monolith) is essential for a 6-month window: it removes the pressure to get it right the first time and enables roll-back in <5 minutes. Data consistency is bifurcated: payments and orders are critical and require stronger guarantees (event sourcing); inventory can accept eventual consistency but requires idempotent operations. Team coordination is addressed by making contracts explicit (specs first, implementation second) rather than relying on verbal agreement.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Extraction Sequencing Strategy",
        "Operational Infrastructure Requirements"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Feature flags and fallback to monolith are essential for risk mitigation; without them, the pressure to get services right first-time is unbearable in a 6-month window",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.11,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Payment and order data should use event sourcing for strong consistency; inventory can accept eventual consistency but requires idempotent operations",
          "truth": 0.81,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Written OpenAPI specs before implementation prevent ad-hoc API design and team coordination failure",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.16,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "6-Month Outcome and Success Criteria",
      "content": "The realistic deliverable at month 6 is: (1) Auth service in production, reliable, boring; (2) Payment service in production, PCI-compliant, processor-wrapper pattern; (3) Inventory service partially extracted (60% functionality), with 40% remaining in monolith; (4) Monolith reduced to ~250K LOC; (5) Order fulfillment still monolithic (intentional, not a failure); (6) Inter-service call patterns emerging but not yet optimized. This is explicitly framed as success, not as incomplete work. The team will have proven the extraction pattern, reduced risk surface, and positioned itself for 12 more months of refinement. The 6-month window is treated as the first sprint of a longer migration, not as the finish line. Extracted services are expected to be boring and reliable; optimizing them for performance is deferred.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Extraction Sequencing Strategy",
        "Technical Debt and Monolith Reduction"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "At month 6, the realistic outcome is 3 extracted services (auth, payment, partial inventory), 50% reduction in monolith LOC, and proved extraction pattern",
          "truth": 0.68,
          "indeterminacy": 0.26,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Completing full inventory extraction is not required by month 6; 60% extraction with 40% remaining in monolith is acceptable",
          "truth": 0.72,
          "indeterminacy": 0.22,
          "falsity": 0.06
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "declared_losses": [
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Detailed account of how to handle eventual consistency in inventory (read-your-own-writes semantics, consistency windows, conflict resolution during stock adjustments)",
      "shed_from": "Extraction Sequencing Strategy",
      "why": "The response prioritized high-level architecture over implementation details. A full treatment of eventual consistency patterns (CQRS, event sourcing for inventory views) would have extended the response by 2000+ words and exceeded practical conversational bounds. This detail is deferred to a follow-up conversation when the user asks about inventory synchronization.",
      "category": "context_pressure"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Analysis of how to migrate the existing 500K LOC codebase incrementally without complete rewrites. For example: which auth functions to extract first, how to maintain compatibility with legacy code during extraction, dual-write strategies for the database transition.",
